600 Water
1 Vegetable Stock Pot
300 Bulgur Wheat
3 Garlic Clove
2 Red Pepper
1 Yellow Pepper
3 Spring Onion
4 Pork Medallion
2 Cornflour
2 Chinese Rice Vinegar
4 Kecap Manis

Bring the water (as specified in the ingredient list) to the boil in a pot with the vegetable stock pot. Pour in the bulgur wheat, place a lid on the pot and rest off the heat for 25 mins, or until the water has completely soaked into the wheat.

Meanwhile, peel and chop the garlic. Remove the core from the peppers and chop into bite-sized chunks. Thinly slice the spring onion, separating the white and green parts.

Cut the pork into bite-sized cubes and season with a pinch of salt and pepper. Sprinkle the cornflour onto a plate and coat your pork thoroughly on all sides.

Turn your hob to high and heat a splash of oil in a frying pan. Line a large plate with kitchen paper. When the pan is hot, add half your pork and fry until brown (about 4 mins). Transfer your pork to the lined plate to drain the oil, then fry the remainder and add to the plate too.

In a small bowl, mix the vinegar with a sprinkle of sugar (if you have some). Stir until your sugar has dissolved then set aside.

Rinse the frying pan used for your pork then put on medium-high heat. Add a splash of oil and cook your garlic and your whites of your spring onion for 1 minute. Add your pepper chunks and cook for 4 mins. Add the ketjap manis and your vinegar mixture and bring to a simmer.

Return your pork to the pan and stir thoroughly. Continue cooking for 2-3 mins. Season with salt and pepper, if needed.

Serve your pork with your bulgur wheat on the side. Sprinkle with your remaining spring onion and enjoy!